text: Good afternoon. Welcome to the Johnson Space Center open house. We think we've exceeded our expectations. We thought we'd have about 20,000 people show up today just to the open house. We think that we're well over 70,000 now. So... We thank you. We certainly thank you for your support. I'm Sue Garman. I'm the Executive Assistant to the Director of the Johnson Space Center. And on behalf of all the employees here, we're happy to have you here. We're happy to have all of our friends and neighbors in. And glad that you support the United States Space Program. We hope that you have taken advantage and will for the rest of the time that the Space Center is open today of the unique opportunity to look around and see the kind of work that we do to help make sure that we have a human spaceflight program. This last session deals with the historic Apollo 13 mission, and it features four of the flight controllers who successfully brought the astronauts home. We're going to follow this with a question and answer session. Let me introduce them in order from my right on across. first is Gene Kranz. Gene holds a degree in Aeronautical Engineering. Prior to coming to NASA, he worked as a flight loads test engineer at McDonnell Aircraft. He served as a pilot in the Air Force, and he worked as a flight test engineer at Holloman Air Force Base. He joined NASA in 1960 and worked as a flight director in both the Mercury and Gemini programs. As the flight director for the Apollo and the Skylab programs, he led the team in mission control during the first lunar landing and the successful return of the Apollo 13 crew. During the Shuttle Era, Gene served as the Deputy Director of Flight Operations and the Director of Mission Operations. He retired from NASA in 1994. Jerry Griffin holds a degree in Aeronautical Engineering. Prior to coming to NASA, he served as an officer in the Air Force and he worked as an aerospace engineer with the Douglas Aircraft Company. He joined NASA in 1964 and he worked as a flight controller for all of the Gemini flights and as a flight director for all of the 11 Apollo missions. His positions at NASA included Assistant Administrator for Legislative Affairs, Deputy Associate Administrator for Manned Space Flight, Deputy Director of the Dryden Flight Research Center, Associate Administrator for External Relations, and Deputy Director of the Kennedy Space Center. He also served as a Director of the Johnson Space Center from 1982 until his retirement from NASA. Next is Jerry Bostic. Jerry holds a degree in civil engineering. He joined NASA as an aerospace engineer at the Langley Space Center in 1962 and he transferred to Houston in the same year. He worked as a flight controller for the Mercury, Gemini, Apollo, and Skylab missions. He was the flight dynamics officer for the Apollo 13 mission. His other positions at NASA included executive assistant to the NASA administrator, deputy manager of the space shuttle program, and director of mission support. Since leaving NASA, he has worked as the vice president of space systems for Grumman Corporation, and is currently the director of business development for Northrop Grumman Technical Services. And on my far right is John Aron. John holds a degree in physics. He joined NASA in 1964 as a vehicle systems engineer for the Gemini program. John was a flight controller for the Gemini and Apollo missions. During the Skylab program, he was the section head for electrical power, sequential, and instrumentation systems. His other positions at NASA have included management positions working with spacecraft software, management positions with the space station program, acting assistant administrator for exploration, and assistant director of engineering at the Johnson Space Center. He is currently the manager of the systems engineering office. Let's welcome all of them. Okay, this is going to be a very informal session up here. We haven't rehearsed this script. The Apollo 13 I think really had several key points associated with it. The first thing was I look at it as a real miracle of leadership. We were fortunate, all of us up here, to grow up under some exemplary leaders. We had George Miller. We had Jim McDivitt, George Lowe. We had Chris Kraft, Deke Slayton, Dr. Gilruth. And each of these people gave true meaning to authority with responsibility. So that when it came time to fly missions, these folks were with us every step of the way. They gave us the job and they expected us to do it. And I think that was one of the real keys to the success of that mission and all the missions that we had in the program. The second element was associated with the people. The people were universally young, they were convinced that the impossible was truly possible, they had gone through very rigorous training they had grown up in the business of mission operations. and we would spend the days, weeks, months, and eventually the years together not only working in mission control, but working in our offices, building the game plan, developing confidence in ourselves, and confidence in each other. The training personnel we had were the best in the world, because those were the ones that gave us the can-do attitude, the never surrender, and with that kind of a background, we moved into the Apollo program. There had been several very key missions in Apollo, and everyone up here worked those missions. We went to the moon in Apollo 11. We had difficulties getting down to the surface, but we made it. Apollo 12, we were struck by lightning, and I believe Jerry was the flight director there, and you've got another key guy on his right, John Aaron, who made the calls to get the spacecraft back to life again. Apollo 13 came along, so we were no... The kinds of problems that we had, we were convinced we could work and lick. So I think we were ready at 55-55 when the problem occurred on board the spacecraft. Everything had been normal up to that time. We'd gone through two team rotations. We had four teams going. We had Milt Wendler, the maroon flight director, who launched the mission. I believe Jerry actually did the transposition and docking. I had the lunar orbit insertion. I was going to do the lunar ascent. And Glenn Lunny was really the guy who was sort of making sure that us rookies in the non-trajectory business did our work properly and by the book. So, we had gone through the two team successions and everything was ops normal up to that point. Jerry, why don't you say? Yeah, I'd like to pick up on a couple of and amplify a couple of James remarks. I think at the time, well I know at the time in my own case, in Apollo 13, I was 35. five, I probably had more responsibility at age 34, 35, 36, than I've ever had before or since. And as Gene said, this was really important in Apollo 13, because when we did get into trouble, the senior management of the agency and the senior management of the center really only had one question of us on the flight control team is what can we do to help you? They really did leave the decision-making a bunch of young people. I think Gene was probably 37. And he was probably the oldest flight director on that flight. I think Jon Aaron was 27 or something like that. Jerry was 28. No, you weren't. Anyway, it was a young person's game. And then sometime when I reflect, and obviously in this session we'll get into more of the problem and how we fixed it and that sort of thing. But one of the things I thought about after the flight was over, and this didn't occur to me during the mission, as soon as we landed every one of these lunar missions, we didn't have much time to dwell on it. We had to go on to the next one. Well, that was no exception in this case. The only difference is we'd had this big problem. And the amazing thing to me is that after we landed, this was in April 1970, we had a complete accident investigation. We had a set of congressional hearings. We had to go fix the problem, redo the command module pretty extensively in the oxygen system, and we went back to the moon in less than a year. In fact, we were there and about ten months later we flew Apollo 14. Now that shows you another difference in attitude that existed 25 years ago, is when you had a problem and you had this to have this adversity to overcome, rather than wailing and gnashing of teeth and worrying about the future, you set the problem right and charged it on because you had not changed your initial goals. And I think that was a very fortunate time, with today's oversight and other kinds of problems that you get into, it would be extremely difficult well, to do what we did in 1970-71, to get the program back on track. So I think it's a very interesting historical perspective. And it's one we probably ought to keep in mind for the future. Finally, and I'm not going to say too much about it. Jerry Bostic ought to say something about the Apollo. They've asked us to talk a little bit about the Apollo 13 movie. It was a great experience. Jerry and I got to work on it as technical advisors. and it was an interesting way that project got started, but maybe Jerry will fill you in on that. And I really do think it's brought alive a lot of interest in the American public. It's taken us back 25 years and it's brought up some of these successes and overcoming of failures that I think is a very positive thing and it's good for the space program. Jerry. I had forgotten how much older you guys were. The movie has brought a lot of attention back to the mission, and it has caused all of us to reflect a lot on what happened 25 years ago. It was kind of strange to me at first that almost everyone asked the same question, Weren't you guys scared to death when the accident happened? Weren't you running around wringing your hands and pulling your hair out? And of course, the answer was no. And then the next question is why? Well, the only reason I can think why is because of the training that we had had, which was, I don't think we fully understood it at the time. But it's good training for any endeavor that you undertake, and that is to try to anticipate the problems that are going to happen, have a plan of action for anything that you can dream of that will possibly come up. But, in reality, after the accident occurred, into the next four days while we tried to figure out collectively how to get the crew home, we didn't have a lot of time to worry about anything except the task at hand. And there was a time to wring her hands and pull her hair. It was a great example of teamwork over the past 10 years or so, anyway. In the aerospace industry, there's been a lot of attention on total quality management and things like that. that and it occurred to me not too long ago that even though we didn't know it at the time, that's what we were all practicing here at the Johnson Space Center 25 and 30 years ago. It was true teamwork. Everybody knew the task that they had to do and we tried to do the best that we could. John? Maybe I could present a little bit of what my role was in this mission and give you my impressions of what was accomplished. I was a systems engineer, I manned one of the controller consoles in the Mission Control Center as Gene said. My job was, since there was two spaceships involved going to the moon, one to be the mothership to transport the landing craft to the moon called the lunar module, I was in charge of all the subsystems, all the vital systems and utilities that kept both the mothership alive and sustain the crew, so I had a very important responsibility. My role in the mission was initially to be on the launch phase team, as Gene mentioned, and that would rotate me to be in the landing phase. I wound up being on a part of the team that was charged with the awful decision of trying to decide whether or not to shut the mother ship down as a result of this explosion, how much longer should we spend our precious power diagnosing this system versus a decision to shut it down and depends really on the lifeboat. Having been a part of that decision process, we then, while the lifeboat team tried to understand how to get the mother ship back in the vicinity of the Earth safely, I was charged with the awful responsibility of leading a team that says, given that the lifeboat team can get us back in the vicinity of the Earth, is there any way to turn this thing back on, given this limited power that we've got? The reason I bring you through that sequence is not only acquaintance you with kind of what my responsibility was but I think the thing that that I'm most left with that mission is as I sum it up to people my conclusion is it works. Now what I mean by that is any complex endeavor like going to the moon which that was a very complex endeavor. We on the ground here as part of design team you know we did design, design, design, and we did train, train, train and what if planning, try to cover every contingency, we train day and night. I think what this mission serves as is a model that there is a method by which you not only can train and design for all the cases you think will happen to you, but that very method and model and training process will help you react in a very successful way to things you never envisioned and never thought you could handle. We wound up with a situation that we never trained for. The spacecraft, the mission was certainly never designed for. But those fundamental methods in this management team and this process served to be the thing that got us home. I think that's a model for our future that says complex endeavors. There is a method to handle the things you don't really train for, but the things you don't. As usual, John is being extremely modest about his role in the mission. He headed a team after the accident that had to try to figure out and did how that we could get the spacecraft back with the consumables that we had on board. We didn't have enough water. We didn't have enough electricity. We didn't have enough oxygen. And being a guy who worried about how to get the people home from an in-flight trajectory standpoint, if I wanted to burn the engine or turn the platform on or anything to use the guidance system, I have to go to John to try to convince him that I needed 5 amp hours. I need to do an amp. That's not it. One in! For ten minutes. Actually, at the time... We were at 55 hours into the mission. We were at our second rotation of the flight control team, and it takes a while to get into the groove. We always look towards that translunar phase as sort of a way to come up to speed in all of our homework doing the final tag-ups with the various flight controllers we got and just get ourselves ready for the events that would occur once we went into lunar orbit. We had finished the TV show, secured the downlink and one of the things the flight controllers always pride themselves in is getting the crew to sleep on time and not having to wake them up during the sleep period. We were in the process of doing this when we asked the crew to go through a cryo-stir And we did this because the cryogenics tended to stratify in the tank, and we always liked to get our best measurement gauging on the cryotankage during the crew's sleep period because we knew pretty much what their metabolic use was, so we could get a good handle on our consumables. So we told the crew to stir the cryos, and Jack Swigert reached over, and he flipped four switches. Down on the ground within just the next three seconds, three controllers reported a problem. First one was the guidance officer who identified that we had a hardware restart. ENCO came in and said, ENCO is the communications officer, that we had switched from narrow to wide beam and simultaneously with that we got a call from the E-com's position that we had a main B-undervolt and about that time... Hey, excuse me, Jack Swigert first, and then a level second came down and said, Houston, we've got a problem. And it was funny how your mind works because the first thing I thought, which one's he talking about? Is he talking about the hardware restart, the main P under fault, or the communications problem. And that wiped clear in just a second. And then you started listening up to the loops, and all the controllers started to come on loops, because virtually everybody in the control center had some — were seeing some symptoms of the problems that occurred. And it was really confusing for those first two, three, to four minutes, because the reports kept coming in. Nothing made sense. The crew was changing the configuration on board the spacecraft, so about the time we'd get ready to make some recommendation to them, that recommendation would change because they had changed something else. Ah, the GNNC or the guidance and control guy was worried because he was seeing a lot of pressure decay on the quads, the RCS jets that we use for attitude control. And this is because we didn't know it was at that time an explosion. But a shock had gone through the spacecraft that it closed a lot of the valves. Actually, we were just bringing the propellant and the manifold to the jets and the manifold pressures were decaying. the spacecraft was incapable of being controlled. It was a very difficult three or four minutes. But then after about three to three and a half minutes, the basic discipline and the training of the team and the quality the controllers started to take over. In particular, the control guy recognized that the jets had been, the valves had been closed and that's why we couldn't control attitude. So we've now started to that solve our attitude problem. The communications guy came up and said to say, until we get our attitude problem nailed down let's use the Omni antenna. So now we were getting information constantly into the spacecraft. The guidance officer by this time very quickly had come up and said he had the time of the hardware restart so now we could start tracing back in our data at the possible time this occurred. So the control team, over the next 10 to 15 minutes continued to work their problems with one exception and that was the the Ecom Cae Liebergat who had the consistent problems associated with the fuel cells and the cryogenics and it became obvious we were chasing the instrumentation problems early but by the time we were about 10 to 15 minutes into this episode it became obvious that we were seeing some real problems but but we were still dubious about what information we could truly believe. But the crew, the controllers, the entire team was coming to the conclusion that we had problems in fuel cells, problems in cryos, and it looked like at least two fuel cells were done. And about this time, about fifteen minutes into this entire episode, we were in the process of a changing shift. Glen Lanney had come in and turned to Glen and told him to get a hold of Chris, that he had better get in because we're in deep, serious trouble. And it was just frustrating to see the lifeblood and the fuel cells and cryoscaping and not being able to do anything about it. And then Jim Lovell came down and said, we're venting something. And as soon as he said venting, that then synced, I think, everybody in the team. I think everybody sort of sent a chill down your spine. that says, my God, we had some type of an explosion, and in my mind, the first thought I had was survival, that we're now in a survival situation, and these guys up here, somewhere along the line, in their careers, flight controllers, have looked at this thing we call the doomsday scenario, and you look it straight in the face, and it sort of gets your attention. Go ahead. Interestingly enough, because Gene and I have talked about this, when the accident first happened, And our thought was, now what do we got to do to go ahead with this landing mission? Yeah. And I know you got to that survival mode in a couple of steps, because that was the way we were trained. When it happens, what do we have to do now to make sure we can still land OK? And Jim Lovell was thinking the same way. He said, yeah, we've had some kind of problem, but we'll get this fixed and go on and land on the moon. It's interesting how you kind of step down and all of a sudden you say, there's no more options left. Now the game is to get them back and forget the mission of going to the moon or- We never trained this doomsday scenario because it's non-beneficial. I mean, you end up killing the crew and the controllers end up going home. So you never train to this. So all of the training that we have, there's always some way out. And that's the way we're trained. And it went through my mind, in fact, in the voice loops. Let's not do anything that's going to blow the mission. I was still thinking, well, if we can't land on the Moon, we're going to go into orbit around the Moon, kind of thing. So it's, the training process is, it's interesting how your mind down modes under this kind of situation. We continued to work on this thing for the best part of another hour. We recognized very quickly, and we had two things going for us. In Apollo 9 mission, we had built something we call the lifeboat procedures. procedures and about 45 minutes into this crisis we went and proceeded to start digging out these lifeboat procedures because once you do something like that you always save it. The other thing that was useful on this mission was we had done a lot of maneuvers using the LEM spacecraft during Apollo 9 and all that data was in archive, so we really started going two directions. One got to get the data out of archives from the Apollo 9 mission and the rest of controllers to dig out their lifeboat procedures. So I think that's all. I'll let these guys continue for a while. Yeah. Interesting. And I just, I don't know what made me think of this, but it'll show you a little bit how, by the time we got to Apollo 13, how we were thinking about going to the moon. There's a few errors. I know some of the NASA people could find little errors in the thing that they weren't quite right. But the technical track in what we did and how we did it was very accurate.
